04294nam a22005175i 9780804780131DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047801317 a10.1515/97808047801312doi  a(DE-B1597)581594  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHT1523.N63 2000eb 7aSOC0200002bisacsh04a305.8/007/21 aNobles, Melissa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aShades of Citizenship :bRace and the Census in Modern Politics /cMelissa Nobles. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tPreface -- t1. Race, Censuses, and Citizenship -- t2. "The Tables present plain matters of fact": Race Categories in U.S. Censuses -- t3. With "time ... , they will be white": Brazilian Censuses and National Identity -- t4. Identities in Search of Bodies: Popular Campaigns Around Censuses -- t5. Counting by Race: More than Numbers -- tAppendix: Race Categories and Instructions to Census Enumerators of U.S. Population Censuses, 1850-1960 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book explores the politics of race, censuses, and citizenship, drawing on the complex history of questions about race in the U.S. and Brazilian censuses. It reconstructs the history of racial categorization in American and Brazilian censuses from each country’s first census in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries up through the 2000 census. It sharply challenges certain presumptions that guide scholarly and popular studies, notably that census bureaus are (or are designed to be) innocent bystanders in the arena of politics, and that racial data are innocuous demographic data. Using previously overlooked historical sources, the book demonstrates that counting by race has always been a fundamentally political process, shaping in important ways the experiences and meanings of citizenship. This counting has also helped to create and to further ideas about race itself. The author argues that far from being mere producers of racial statistics, American and Brazilian censuses have been the ultimate insiders with respect to racial politics. For most of their histories, American and Brazilian censuses were tightly controlled by state officials, social scientists, and politicians. Over the past thirty years in the United States and the past twenty years in Brazil, however, certain groups within civil society have organized and lobbied to alter the methods of racial categorization. This book analyzes both the attempt of America’s multiracial movement to have a multiracial category added to the U.S. census and the attempt by Brazil’s black movement to include racial terminology in census forms. Because of these efforts, census bureau officials in the United States and Brazil today work within political and institutional constraints unknown to their predecessors. Categorization has become as much a “bottom-up” process as a “top-down” one.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCensus. 0aGroup identity. 0aRace. 4aLaw -- Law and Society. 4aPolitics -- United States. 4aSociology -- Race, Class, and Gender. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Minority Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478013140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804780131423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804780131/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles